conclude that that form is &quot;the best&quot;. If neither form is &quot;equal t=\r\no&quot; supreme being, how can you really compare the different qualities of two=\r\n forms?\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;Anyway, this renders your =\r\n(3) a meaningless issue. Whether that line refers to Krishna alone or not i=\r\ns irrelevant, for, in either case, &quot;swayam bhagavan&quot; cannot mean &quot;a personi=\r\nfication of the entirety of supreme being&quot;. Before you wonder whether it re=\r\nfers to Krishna alone or not, first figure out what &quot;swayam bhagavan&quot; actua=\r\nlly means, in a way that is not inconsistent with verses that follow! If no=\r\n form is &quot;equal to&quot; supreme being and every form is a &quot;subset&quot; of supreme b=\r\neing (like a cloud in sky), what is the meaning of &quot;swayam bhagavan&quot;???\n&gt; &gt;=\r\n=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;Regarding (4), Parasara\n&gt;  identifi=\r\ned 4 avataras as 100% divine, with no jivamsa, and identified the source of=\r\n divinity in each of them. He only gave objective information and did not g=\r\nive any subjective judgment on who is the best, which Suta apparently did.\n=\r\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;I have not read BV Purana. If you can quote some verses before=\r\n and after, I can comment. Any comparison between avataras WILL have to be =\r\nunder some subjective context. I don&#39;t know the context of Suta&#39;s statement=\r\n you allude to.\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;Though any comparison is subjective, I will be=\r\n surprised if someone considers the other two poornavataras of Vishnu as th=\r\ne &quot;best&quot; avataras. But, I will not be surprised if different people conside=\r\nr Rama and Krishna as the most perfect avataras. Sun and Moon are the lumin=\r\naries and show soul and mind, which clearly have a primary significance com=\r\npared to other aspects of consciousness! So Rama and Krishna are bound to b=\r\ne seen as the best by different people. However, what Suta\n&gt;  apparently sa=\r\nid can only be a subjective view under some context.\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;*=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0 *\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;Regarding (2): Kala means a part or a phase. Moon has=\r\n 16 phases (representing 16 tithis, including Amavasya and Pournima), but S=\r\nun has only one phase - he is always full and bright!\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;Just lik=\r\ne Moon, mind has many moods, even a perfected one. A perfected mind goes th=\r\nrough those moods with full awareness of underlying reality, whereas an imp=\r\nerfect mind experiences them under delusion. But it is the nature of Moon/m=\r\nind to have variations. Sun/soul OTOH has no such variations.\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;=\r\nKrishna may show Vishwaroopa oneday, run away from battlefield another day =\r\n(e.g. Jarasandha), do amazing miracles oneday and play clever tricks anothe=\r\nr day. There is a lot more variety to his personality than Rama&#39;s. Now, doe=\r\ns that make him better or worse than Rama? Well, that is\n&gt;  a *subjective* =\r\nmatter.\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;Regarding (1): Parasara sa=\r\nid that paramatmamsa is present in several beings such a planets, Brahma, S=\r\nhiva, their consorts, etc. Grahas sustain the world appearance in conscious=\r\nness by grasping it based on karmaphala. So they stand for different qualit=\r\nies of Vishnu that sustain the world appearance. So Vishnu&#39;s avataras are a=\r\nssociated with grahas. But Pararsara said that avataras can descend from th=\r\ne paramatmamsa present in several other beings (e.g. Shiva, Parvati, Ashwin=\r\ns, Maruts etc). Unfortunately, we have meagre understanding what various de=\r\nities stand for, what forces play a role in creating, sustaining and destro=\r\nying the world appearance in consciousness. People talk too much about Veda=\r\nnta (end of Veda) and there is hardly any understanding of Veda. When it co=\r\nmes to Puranic stories, we think in terms of\n&gt;  superficial stories and not=\r\n in terms of how it maps to what happens in consciousness.\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;Moh=\r\nini was an avatara of Vishnu + Maheshwari. Nara & Narayana were incarnation=\r\ns of Narayana (i.e. Brahma + Vishnu + Shiva). I don&#39;t know about Dhanvantar=\r\ni and will pass for today. Dattatreya again was an incarnation of Shiva + V=\r\nishnu + Brahma. Balarama is an incarnation of great serpent Adi Sesha (like=\r\n Lakshmana).\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;We need to go deeper into what they all stand for=\r\n esoterically and what role they play in the functioning of consciousness, =\r\nto understand this more. Hopefully another day..\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 =\r\n*\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;Adwaitins who are skeptical about notions taught by Parasara=\r\n (paramatmamsa, jivatmamsa, different sources of paramtmamsa etc) should re=\r\nalize one thing. Though all is Brahman, all did not come from Brahman in on=\r\ne step. It all evolved in many steps\n&gt;  and correspondingly there are some =\r\nsteps in the process of liberation!\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;If a character in my dream=\r\n tonight overcomes its conditioning in the dream, it will simply merge back=\r\n into my mind and not into Brahman yet. Of course, it cannot do even that u=\r\nntil I actually will it. It is after all a character created and sustained =\r\nin my mind!\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;Same thing applies to us!\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;Vedanta is =\r\nnot wrong. But it is relevant and applicable at &quot;anta&quot;, i.e. the end. Most =\r\nof us may not yet be anywhere near &quot;the end&quot;.\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=\r\n=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt;=\r\n &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;BTW, I distinguished between Vishnu and \n&gt; Narayana above. If y=\r\nou study Narayana sooktam and Vishnu Sooktam, you \n&gt; can understand the dif=\r\nference. In Vaishnava traditions, they are \n&gt; considered one, but, strictly=\r\n speaking, that is inaccurate. Of course, \n&gt; you can reach Narayana through=\r\n Vishnu. But then, you can reach Narayana \n&gt; through Rudra or Bhairava as w=\r\nell!\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;&gt; I am afraid the world will =\r\nkeep getting more and more convinced that\n&gt; &gt;&gt; this specific list of dasava=\r\ntaras represent a parable of evoluion\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;The *world*? You mean th=\r\ne world of Rajarshi? ;-)\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;World accepts 10 avataras where Kalki=\r\n will be the 10th (and not 9th as you suggested, to fit your notion of evol=\r\nution). Even those who are uncomfortable with Buddha replace him with someo=\r\nne else rather than make it 9 avataras. World neither thinks much about thi=\r\ns nor draws hasty conclusions. World really does not care about this..\n&gt; &gt;=\r\n=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;Best regards,\n&gt; &gt;Narasimha\n&gt; &gt;--------\n&gt; &gt;Astrology & Spiritualit=\r\ny Resources: http://www.VedicAstrologer.org \n&gt; &gt;--------\n&gt; &gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n=\r\n&gt; &gt;&gt;________________________________\n&gt; &gt;&gt; From: rajarshi nandy &lt;rajarshi14@=\r\n...&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;To: &quot;vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com&quot; &lt;vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com&gt; =\r\n\n&gt; &gt;&gt;Sent: Tuesday, May 7, 2013 3:38 PM\n&gt; &gt;&gt;Subject: Re: [vedic-wis