iri=\r\nt of comprehension, Saturn - spirit of patience & persistence, Venus - spir=\r\nit of happiness etc) and the story of corresponding avatara DOES have a hig=\r\nhly meaningful connection, esoterically speaking. After all, esoterically i=\r\ns how you really need to understand any higher scriptures and notions in th=\r\nem.\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;If we take scriptures literally instead and draw l=\r\nopsided conclusions, some would conclude that Shiva is the &quot;supreme&quot; one an=\r\nd other deities are &quot;inferior&quot;; some would conclude that Surya is the &quot;supr=\r\neme&quot; one and other deities are &quot;inferior&quot;; and so on.\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;=\r\n*=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0 *=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=C2=A0=\r\n=C2=A0=C2=A0 *\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;On a different note, someone may think =\r\nthat Kali, being Aadyaa, is superior\n&gt;  to Tara and like Kali more. But, so=\r\nme learned yogis have declared them to be essentially the same and some scr=\r\niptures even prohibited differentiating between them. As I see it, the diff=\r\nerence between them is too subtle for even rishis to clearly comprehend. Pe=\r\nople seeing some significant difference between them are, I am afraid, mere=\r\nly projecting their own conditioning. Same in the case of Krishna and Rama.=\r\n Both were=C2=A0 perfectly detached and fully divine karma yogis.\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;=\r\n=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;If we think about it, perfected mind (paramatma aspect repres=\r\nented by Moon) and soul (paramatma aspect represented by Sun) are not reall=\r\ny that different. So I am afraid Krishna and Rama are not that different, t=\r\nhough the specifics of their stories may be different.\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;=\r\n&gt;One last word though. If someone truly believes that Krishna is superior t=\r\no Rama and worships Krishna (or vice versa!), I am very happy for such a pe=\r\nrson. My arguments are more for the sake of sharing thinking/knowledge and =\r\npushing the boundaries of understanding in the long run, than changing the =\r\nminds of anyone in the short run. In the end, everyone of us will have to g=\r\no through one&#39;s own cycles of various tamasik, rajasik and saattwik stages =\r\nof evolution before one starts grasping some fistfuls of Reality. These con=\r\ncepts are too subtle for anyone to convince others or be absolutely confide=\r\nnt oneself!\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;Krishnarpanamastu, Narasimha -------- Astr=\r\nology & Spirituality Resources: http://www.vedicastrologer.org/\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;----=\r\n----\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;=C2=A0\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;From: rajarshi nandy &lt;rajarshi14@=\r\n...&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;To: &quot;vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com&quot; &lt;vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.c=\r\nom&gt; \n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;Sent: Saturday, May 4, 2013 7:34 AM\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;Subject: Re: [vedi=\r\nc-wisdom] Comparing Dasavataras!\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;=C2=A0 =\r\n\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;Namaste,\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;Jai Ma!\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;=\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;I have a different view point. Let me write down as I see it, i=\r\nn point by point manner.\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;1. In the Bhagwata Puran=\r\na, there are a list of 22 Avataras of Vishnu. In this list of 22, Varaha Av=\r\natara is the 2nd Avatara, and Matsya is the 10th Avatara. Dattatreya, Nara-=\r\nnarayana,Vyasa Deva himself are in this list, and then the Bhagawata Purana=\r\n goes ontu mention that the Avatars of Vishnu are innumerable. In the 10th =\r\nCanto, Vyasa says all these Avatars, and innumerable others, are amsas of t=\r\nhe Supreme Being while Krshna is &quot;swayam Bhagawan.&quot;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;=\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt;2. Of these various possible Avataras, 10, or rather 9 as I believe, are=\r\n/have been accorded special mention and significance across various Hindu s=\r\npiritual literature, specially those which were composed in the Kali-Yuga, =\r\nnamely the Puranas.[When Krshna was alive, it was Kali-Sandhya, his physica=\r\nl presence had curtailed the full effect of Kali,once he left his body, Kal=\r\ni started in full flow. All Puranas were composed after this, hence these a=\r\nre scriptures of the Kali-Yuga, as are Tantras]\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;3=\r\n. These 10/9 Avataras have a fixed sequence of appearance. Matysa, Kurma, V=\r\naraha, Narasimha, Vamana, Parashurama, Rama, Krshna, (Buddha) and Kalki. Th=\r\nere is an unmistakeable connection of the form and sequence of these main a=\r\nvatars with the evolution of life on earth. From the aquatic, to the amphib=\r\nian, to the land-animal, to the half-animal-half-man, to the dwarf man (fir=\r\nst human life form who immediately takes possession of this earth represent=\r\ned by Vamana&#39;s 3 steps), to the Rajashik avatara of Parashurama moving arou=\r\nnd with an axe, to the Sattwa Guna Avatara of Rama, to the Nirguna Avatara =\r\nof Krshna. Also, this indicates that spirituality is not to be separated in=\r\nto another world, but is a progressive realization of the various manifesta=\r\ntion and potentials that lie inherent in the consciousness and its developm=\r\nent through various life-forms. Larger spirituality of earth and evolution =\r\ngo hand in hand. That is Nature&#39;s grand design for life on\n&gt;  earth.\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;=\r\n&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;4. In this specifc context, I am only focusing on the p=\r\narable of these main 9/10 Avatars. It is not my contention that if one wors=\r\nhips say Matysa Avatara, one will not attain to a state of liberation of th=\r\ne soul. As is the nature of spiritual cosmology in Hinduism, any Devata can=\r\n lead a person to any depth of realization. And each one of the Avatars of =\r\nVishnu are self-realized in their own way and can be consider super-massive=\r\n spiritual dynamos.\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;=C2=A05. Of these, n=\r\naturally, Rama and Krshna are most adored because they represent a stage of=\r\n evolution, both inside as well as outside, which society can relate of muc=\r\nh easier, in this age. Rama represents, for me, the stage of most satwic mi=\r\nnd. A satwic mind is in control of itself. It known how to transform the an=\r\nimal tendencies within and without - monkeys - into a constructive force fo=\r\nr a greater purpose. However, as with a state of full Sattwa Guna, there ca=\r\nn be instances, even though few, of dejection. For it is static in nature a=\r\nnd will change only when circumstances force it to. As per the Valmiki Rama=\r\nyana, Rama did feel dejected while searching for Sita in the forest. He did=\r\n have a moments fear before the final assault on Ravana, which was dispelle=\r\nd by Agsatha when the later revealed the stotra of the Sun to Rama. At the =\r\nend of the final battle, Rama tells Sita, in a most dispassionate manner, t=\r\nhat he killed Ravana not to rescue her, but it\n&gt;  was the Dharma to do so, =\r\nand to unhold his family honour. That too was the dharma of that age when h=\r\ne lived, family honor. The way I look at this grand epic, and I bow humbly =\r\nto the genius of Rishis Valmiki for representing the things as they are, as=\r\n a scribe, as a poet, as an observer, and not adding his own preferences to=\r\n it anywhere, in the 14 years of tribulation that Rama faced which culminat=\r\ned into his killing Ravana, he changed into the most dispassionate leader, =\r\nsuch that no personal consideration or emotions or passions can overturn th=\r\ne Rajadharma. His life is a lesson of what a true leader must be! Krshna, O=\r\nTOH, had this immaculate detachment right from birth. I am not taking his=\r\n=C2=A0 supernatural feats into account. It is his singular and constant det=\r\nachment from situations, from people, from environment, from circumstances =\r\nthat mark his life. At the age of eight, he decides to leave Vrindavana for=\r\n Mathura. All his friends, his foster parents,\n&gt;  his village-folks who so =\r\nloved him, pleaded with him that it would make no sense for him to leave th=\r\ne shelter, love and comfort of his happy, settled village life and head int=\r\no an unknown destiny and destination. Krshna tried to reason with them, the=\r\nn he understood that they won&#39;t understand, he promised he will return back=\r\n once his work in Mathura is over. He never returned. Later, much later, wh=\r\nen the Gopis came to him asking him to participate in their dance, he oblig=\r\ned. But the moment some of them started getting jealous and possessive of K=\r\nrshna, he removed himself quietly from the scene, saying that he belongs to=\r\n everyone equally and no one has any special right over him. When Shishupal=\r\na abused Krshna, the later merely kept dropping flowers on the floor, smili=\r\nng and counting. The moment the 100th abuse was over, he swiftly cut off Sh=\r\nishupala&#39;s head and was back into his poise. But when Bhurishrava unfairly =\r\naccused Krshna of being a revolutionist\n&gt;  and charlatan, Krshna did not ki=\r\nll him. When Duryodhana, who used to think of Krshna as another black magic=\r\nian, wanted to arrest him, Krshna showed his vikarala roopa in the assembly=\r\n of kings, yet he did not finish the enemies off. The very next moment he w=\r\nas back into his own poised self. Never in the whole Mahabharata is there o=\r\nne instance of his going overboard, never a single shade of depression, equ=\r\nivocation, or lack of confidence in his actions, irrespective of what other=\r\ns say or think of him. And then right in the middle of the greatest war he =\r\nhad the perfect equipoise to deliver the most sublime spiritual philosophy.=\r\n That is why his life remains the best ideal of Karma-Yoga. For a true Karm=\r\na-Yogi by definition can never be dejected. It is impossible. Neither the a=\r\nction nor the results belong to the instrument. When running away from the =\r\nbattle-field and killing Kaliya Yavana, or when advising Bheema to tear apa=\r\nrt Jarashanda, or gesturing Bheema\n&gt;  to hit Duryodhana below the waist, or=\r\n getting Shikhandi to face Bhisma, Krshna, as if by some Divine Intuition, =\r\nknew exactly how the situations must be lined up which would cause the dest=\r\nruction of these people. This kind of knowledge cannot come by the rational=\r\n thinking. But happens when one is constantly and consciously connected to =\r\nthe Universal Force. We do not find these kind of complex situations in the=\r\n Rama Avatara, at least in the Valmiki Ramayana. Of course, if we take the =\r\nAdhbut Ramayana or such other auxilliary texts and retelling, we get a diff=\r\nerent picture. In the Adbhuta Ramayana we have a 1000 headed demon attackin=\r\ng Rama after he kills Ravana, and then Sita turns into Adya Shakti and demo=\r\nlishes the 1000 headed demon and Rama worships her. But if we take only the=\r\n Ramayana and the Mahabharata, the picture that emerges is very clear. Rama=\r\n is the embodiment of Sattwic mind. Therefore he displays all the great cha=\r\nracteristics of satwa, chief\n&gt;  of which is self-control, as well as the oc=\r\ncasional sadness caused due to separation from his wife Sita whom, at least=\r\n until Ravana was destroyed, he loved very dearly. Satwa guna creates a tru=\r\ne saint, but can also cause some grief when the stability is shaken. Krshna=\r\n was gunatita. He had no attachment to anything in this world - man, women,=\r\n deva, danava, friend, enemy - and therefore he was never affected any trac=\r\ne of negative emotion. His Ananda never left him even in the most trying si=\r\ntuations. 6. Buddha was great spiritual force in this world. But I do not s=\r\nee him fit in the scheme of evolutionary Avatars. His realization, the one =\r\nhe advocated, is a static realization, an end in a void. This is clearly de=\r\nnying of the reality of this earth. I find this not in tune with what eithe=\r\nr Rama or Krshna espoused. None of them negated this world. If negation of =\r\nthis world and life is the final aim, then why send so many avatars at cruc=\r\nial stages of\n&gt;  evolutionary development? If the spiritual impact on masse=\r\ns is the reason for Buddha being an Avatara, then why not Jesus or Zorathru=\r\nsta.? They are no less impactful in that sense. But do they fit in the sche=\r\nme of spiritual line that these 9 Avataras of Narayana indicate in a most l=\r\nogical manner? No. As such many vaishnava traditions in parts of India, do =\r\nnot consider Buddha to be an avatara. Realization, to be complete and holis=\r\ntic, must be both static and dynamic, outside of life as well as inside of =\r\nlife. That is why the Tantras formed their own kind of spiritual philosophy=\r\n, of the world as body of Shakti and therefore an object of reverence and r=\r\nealization. 7. The original literature of the Nath Yogis used to mention 9 =\r\nchakras. These are centers of psychological functions. 6 inside the human b=\r\nody and 3 too subtle, or non-developed in most people, even seekers. It is =\r\nmy belief that each of the 9 Avataras - excluding Buddha - correspond to th=\r\ne full\n&gt;  power and force of one of these 9 Chakras. Similarly, the 9 graha=\r\ns, or that which can modify consciousness or allow the consciousness to exp=\r\nlore and express itself is various possiblities, are 9 in number. The lagna=\r\n is a reference point and not a graha. Therefore the chief Avatars who repr=\r\nesent the parable of evolution are nine in number. And the ninth of the seq=\r\nuence is yet to come. 8. I cannot comment on which graha would typically re=\r\npresent which Avatara. I know of what the BPHS says, however, it is my beli=\r\nef - feel free to disagree with it -:)[one cannot rule out some deep-rooted=\r\n corruption of understanding or textual misrepresentation in this Kali-Yuga=\r\n] - that the Atmah among the Avataras has not yet appeared. It will be Kalk=\r\ni, or as Vimalananda seems to say in the Aghora books, Nishkalanka - the st=\r\nainless one. There is only one thing which is perfectly stainless, the Atma=\r\nh .After a Nirguna/Gunatita awastha comes living in the full and complete\n&gt;=\r\n  purity and might and force and strength of the Atmah. By the sheer dint o=\r\nf his purity the last Avatara will burn away opposing forces of this world =\r\nand fulfill the purpose of evolution. Even Krshna used diplomacy at various=\r\n points in his adult life to achieve his ends. Kalki, I am speculating, won=\r\n&#39;t even need that. The white horse and that sword is a metaphor. He will be=\r\n the only one capable enough to rectify the various errors and corruptions =\r\nthat beset our age. Well, this is how I look at the story of Avataras. It i=\r\ns perfectly ok not to agree with my views, but I am reasonably sanguine now=\r\n that this is what is closer to truth. -Regards =C2=A0Rajarshi\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;=\r\n&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;awaktam wyaktimApannam manyantE mAmabuddhayah |param bhAwamaj=\r\nAnanto mamAwyayamanuttamam ||[7:24]\n&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&